## Why This Is Asked

Tests memory ownership across CGO, safe conversion from C to Go, and proper cleanup of C-allocated structs. It also probes concurrent usage patterns and error handling across language boundaries.

## Key Concepts

- CGO memory ownership and free patterns
- Safe conversion of C strings to Go with C.GoString
- Handling NULL pointers from C and propagating errors
- Concurrency: CGO calls from multiple goroutines and potential race conditions
- Header/implementation organization for a small, realistic C API

## Code Example

```javascript
// C header (user.h)
typedef struct { int id; const char* name; const char* email; } User;
User* fetch_user(const char* username);
void free_user(User* u);
```

```javascript
// Minimal C implementation (user.c)
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

typedef struct { int id; const char* name; const char* email; } User;

User* fetch_user(const char* username) {
  if (!username) return NULL;
  User* u = (User*)malloc(sizeof(User));
  if (!u) return NULL;
  u->id = 123;
  u->name = strdup(username);
  u->email = strdup(""" + username + "@example.com");
  return u;
}

void free_user(User* u) {
  if (!u) return;
  free((void*)u->name);
  free((void*)u->email);
  free(u);
}
```

```javascript
// Go binding (cgobox.go)
package cgobox

/*
#include "user.h"
*/
import "C"
import (
  "errors"
  "unsafe"
)

type UserInfo struct {
  ID int
  Name string
  Email string
}

func FetchUser(username string) (UserInfo, error) {
  cstr := C.CString(username)
  defer C.free(unsafe.Pointer(cstr))
  u := C.fetch_user(cstr)
  if u == nil {
    return UserInfo{}, errors.New("fetch_user failed")
  }
  info := UserInfo{ID: int(u.id), Name: C.GoString(u.name), Email: C.GoString(u.email)}
  C.free_user(u)
  return info, nil
}
```

