## Why This Is Asked
This question tests your ability to model cross-language callbacks, manage memory ownership, and handle streaming data in CGO. You must coordinate Go and C lifetimes, ensure safe callbacks from C into Go, and design backpressure-aware consumption.

## Key Concepts
- **CGO callbacks**: Exporting Go functions for C to call safely using cgo export
- **Memory ownership**: C allocates chunks via `malloc`, Go frees them to prevent leaks
- **Streaming via channels**: Using Go channels to receive pushed data from C
- **Backpressure**: Ensuring the consumer can signal when it cannot keep up
- **Thread safety**: Managing concurrent access to shared state between C threads and Go runtime

## Code Example
```c
// cgowa_stream.h
typedef void (*chunk_cb)(const char* data, size_t len, void* user);

void* start_stream(const char* source_id, chunk_cb on_chunk, void* user);
void stop_stream(void* handle);
```

```c
// cgowa_stream.c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <pthread.h>
#include "cgowa_stream.h"

struct stream_context {
    chunk_cb callback;
    void* user;
    pthread_t thread;
    int running;
};

static void* stream_thread(void* arg) {
    struct stream_context* ctx = arg;
    const char* chunks[] = {"{\"id\":1}", "{\"id\":2}", "{\"id\":3}"};

    for (int i = 0; i < 3 && ctx->running; i++) {
        size_t len = strlen(chunks[i]);
        ctx->callback(chunks[i], len, ctx->user);
        sleep(1);
    }
    return NULL;
}

void* start_stream(const char* source_id, chunk_cb on_chunk, void* user) {
    struct stream_context* ctx = malloc(sizeof(struct stream_context));
    ctx->callback = on_chunk;
    ctx->user = user;
    ctx->running = 1;
    pthread_create(&ctx->thread, NULL, stream_thread, ctx);
    return ctx;
}

void stop_stream(void* handle) {
    struct stream_context* ctx = handle;
    ctx->running = 0;
    pthread_join(ctx->thread, NULL);
    free(ctx);
}
```

